rnfix4.5

Session.close() and Connection.close() possibly do not behave correctly (i.e.
inconformant to JSR-914)

The problem is that both methods will NOT wait until message consuming
(onMessage, receive methods) has finished, instead methods called from onMessage
(such as rollback, commit or acknowledge) will throw
"javax.jms.IllegalStateException: [C4055]: Resource in conflict. Concurrent
operations on a session.".

This is possibly not conformant to the JMS specification, see JSR-914 "4.4.1
Closing a Session", paragraph 4:
When session close is invoked, it should not return until its message
processing has been shut down in an orderly fashion. This means that none of
its message listeners are running, and that if there is a pending receive, it has
returned with either null or a message.

On the other hand, it also says:
Closing a transacted session must roll back its transaction in progress. Closing
a client-acknowledged session does NOT force an acknowledge.

This is IMHO somewhat contradictory but I think the current behavior doesn't
help anybody - the problem is that I'm usually _forced_ to call "rollback" if
I'm not committing, otherwise the message will be implicitely committed with the
next transaction, so "closing" from another thread will introduce a _third_ case
in "onMessage" _and_ require my own synchronization (since I may not close a
Session from "onMessage", which also hints at "stop" blocking until "onMessage"
has finished).
This behavior also makes proting from other MQs (tested with Sonic, JBoss)
considerably more difficult as they're behaving as expected.
If "close" just waited for the currently active consumers to complete and not
allowing new ones this would ease things considerably.

This bug is present at least in OpenMQ 4.3, 4.4 and 4.4UR1 (tested all). Test
program attached below.

private void testMqBug() throws Exception {
com.sun.messaging.ConnectionFactory cf=new
com.sun.messaging.ConnectionFactory();
final javax.jms.Connection c=cf.createConnection();
final Session s=c.createSession(true, Session.SESSION_TRANSACTED);
// final Session s=c.createSession(false, Session.CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE);
final Queue q=s.createQueue("PhoenixTestQueue");
final MessageConsumer mc=s.createConsumer(q);
final AtomicBoolean consuming=new AtomicBoolean(false);
mc.setMessageListener(new MessageListener() {
public void onMessage(Message rawMsg) {
consuming.set(true);
System.out.println("consuming started");
try

{ TextMessage msg=(TextMessage)rawMsg; System.out.println("Got message: "+msg.getText()); Thread.sleep(20000); }

catch(Exception ex)

{ System.out.println("Exception while consuming messages"); }

finally {
try

{ s.rollback(); // rawMsg.acknowledge(); }

catch(JMSException jmsex)

{ System.out.println("Error rolling back JMS message"); jmsex.printStackTrace(); }

consuming.set(false);
System.out.println("consuming finished");
}
}
});
c.start();
while(true) {
Thread.sleep(100);
if(consuming.get())

{ System.out.println("Closing session"); s.close(); }

}
}
