nigeldeakin@java.net said:
Marking Fixed

When the broker's queue flow control policy is set to blocking, the message
producer will check the flow control before sending.
When it is blocked, it will wait for its ProducerState instance like this (in
MessageProducerImpl.java):

private synchronized void checkFlowControl(Message message) {
while (flowLimit == 0 && ! isClosed) {
try

{ blocked = true; wait(); blocked = false; }

...
}

And the close() method of ProducerState looks like this:

protected synchronized void close() {
notifyAll();
}

Clearly, when a producer is closed, its related ProducerStates will also be
closed, which will notify the thread waiting on the ProducerState in
checkFlowControl(). In checkFlowControl(), if the producer is closed it should
not wait on ProducerState anymore.

Now we see the close() method of the producer:

public void close() throws JMSException {
...
try {
Enumeration enum2 = producerStates.elements();
while (enum2.hasMoreElements())

{ ProducerState ps = (ProducerState) enum2.nextElement(); ps.close(); // <-- the ProducerState is closed here, which will notify the thread waiting on it }

...
} finally

{ isClosed = true; }

}

Not until the "finally" block the "isClosed" flag is set to true. If a producer
thread has been waiting on a ProducerState, it will be notified by the call to
ProducerState's close() method first, then it checks the "isClosed" flag of the
Producer, and it might not have been set because the close method has not
finished. And the thread will wait for the ProducerState again but no one else
can notify it afterwards.

Possible solution: It should add a "isShutdown" flag and set to true in the
beginning of the close() method of Producer, and checkFlowControl() checks it instead of checking the "isClosed" flag
