c_krebs said:
As far as I figured out, the problem here is that the column <tt>SEQ</tt> is handled case sensitively by the JDBC driver or respectively the PostgreSQL.
On table creation all column names are transformed into the lower case variant. But when inserting the change record, the upper case variant of <tt>SEQ</tt> is used.

As a dirty work around I added a further column named <tt>SEQ</tt> - completely upper-case - to the table having the same values as the lower case variant.
And this seems to work.

```
alter table MQSHARECC45Cgdlite1_MQ add column "SEQ" bigint;
update MQSHARECC45Cgdlite1_MQ set "SEQ" = seq;
alter table MQSHARECC45Cgdlite1_MQ alter "SEQ" set not null;

create or replace function maintain_seq() returns trigger
   AS $$
begin
   if TG_OP = 'INSERT' or TG_OP = 'UPDATE' then
      NEW."SEQ" = NEW.seq;

      return NEW;
   end if;

   return OLD;
end
$$
   LANGUAGE plpgsql;

CREATE TRIGGER trigger_maintain_seq
    BEFORE INSERT OR UPDATE ON MQSHARECC45Cgdlite1_MQ
    FOR EACH ROW
    EXECUTE PROCEDURE maintain_seq();
```

